oawaiver.title: PostgreSQL errors block user authentication in production

comments.body:
The `production` environment server appears to have been rebooted on `Tue 2022-08-09 16:28:54 UTC`:

```bash
pulsys@oawaiver-prod1:~$ last
pulsys   pts/2        tmux(23579).%1   Fri Sep  9 13:39   still logged in
pulsys   pts/1        tmux(23579).%0   Fri Sep  9 13:39   still logged in
pulsys   pts/0        172.20.210.218   Fri Sep  9 13:39   still logged in
pulsys   pts/0        172.20.210.218   Fri Sep  9 13:38 - 13:38  (00:00)

wtmp begins Fri Sep  9 13:38:49 2022
```

```bash
pulsys@oawaiver-prod1:~$ sudo journalctl -k
-- Logs begin at Tue 2022-08-09 16:28:54 UTC, end at Fri 2022-09-09 13:40:08 UTC. --
-- No entries --
pulsys@oawaiver-prod1:~$ date
Fri Sep  9 13:40:16 UTC 2022
```
The PostgreSQL database appears to be intact, I am checking to determine if this is accessible from the production `oawaiver` server.
I have just confirmed that the PostgreSQL database is indeed accessible from the `oawaiver` production server.

Repeated attempts to redeploy the application using `capistrano` results in the following:

```bash
rake aborted!
ActiveRecord::StatementInvalid: PG::InsufficientPrivilege: ERROR:  permission denied for table schema_migrations
```
This should be resolved, as the owner for both the PostgreSQL database and tables needed to be manually updated from the user `postgres` to the user `oawaiver_prod_db_user`

https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/postgresql/tasks/create_db.yml#L22 is where the failure is occurring. This should likely be located within the `postgresql_databases` values.

https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/rails_app/meta/main.yml#L21 includes the `postgresql` `role`, which is, in turn, resolved from https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/oawaiver/meta/main.yml#L19
As this is dependent upon https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/issues/3286, I am going to propose that this is resolved.

orangelight.title: Display Uniform title on Show page

comments.body: My understanding is that the plan is to implement this and get sign-off from Esmé and cataloging with it on staging.

Is it a possibility to treat it like subjects are treated, meaning you can search for a title on each part of the uniform title?

Meaning, for example:

240  _1 $a Sonatas, $m horns (2), $n no. 4-6

You could search
Sonatas
Sonatas, horns (2)
Sonatas, horns (2), no. 4-6

Darwin Scott is a major stakeholder with uniform titles, as they are used extensively in music scores for allowing an efficient browse.

Wait, that led me to a record that does have a Uniform title displayed - https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/SCSB-3263617. It looks like it's coming from `name_uniform_title_1display`, which other records that *do* have a `uniform_title_s` do not have. Clearly more investigation is required.

Uniform titles exist in 2 fields.

130 is used when there is no author.
240 is used when there is a 1xx field for an author.

That SCSB record has a 240 field, while the Bible record has a 130. My hunch is the MARC fields are indexed into 2 different fields.

Yes, looking at Bibdata, it looks like that's what's happening. Now the question is - should we change the indexing of `name_uniform_title_1display` in Bibdata, or change the display of Uniform title in Orangelight? I'm leaning towards the Bibdata side now...
Better example of `name_uniform_title_1display` - https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/99125416143706421

I would think you'd want the values from 130 fields and 240 fields to be in the same indexed field, since there _shouldn't_ be a record that has both a 130 and a 240. Catalogers would likely want to revise the records where both exist.

Marquand items are only allowed to be delivered to Marquand location.  They can not be delivered to other locations.  They are also only allowed to be utilized inside the library.
Additionally Marquand items are the only ones that interface with Ciasoft

Marquand items can be either at 693, in Marquand at Firestone or at Clancy (and additionally on a truck to Clancy, which should not longer be true but there was code for that case)

Marquand items that have the shelf location code(s) marquand$pj and marquand$pv will create requests in SCSB, marquand$x, marquand$pz and marquand$t  are serviced by Aeon. All others will flow into the Clancy workflow 

It’s especially confusing because all the locations are now “remote storage” of some type since the Library is closed for renovations.
@kevinreiss can you please update the above comment with the two marquand locations that are serviced by Aeon?

princeton_ansible.title: Correct user should own postgresql tables as well as databases

comments.body:
If the tables are the only ones owned by the old user name, AND THE OLD USER NAME IS NOT THE `postgres` USER, you can also do `REASSIGN OWNED BY olduser TO newuser;`.

**Don't ever do this with the `postgres` user, though, as that could change the ownership of vital administrative resources.**
This was also the case with the `oawaiver-prod1`, as described within the following issue: https://github.com/pulibrary/oawaiver/issues/83

@kayiwa @leefaisonr and I looked at this today. We think it's related to the [task in the postgresql role that changes the db owner](https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/fcd8c89c3dcdd909b96bd427f148d511d701a4f5/roles/postgresql/tasks/create_users.yml#L41-L55). Currently that task uses the `postgresql_db` module, but we may need to use the [`postgresql_owner`](https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/collections/community/postgresql/postgresql_owner_module.html) module instead.
